ntegration-level concern because the failure mode involves the send module being called prematurely, which requires testing how the approval workflow and send components interact together. A unit test might verify the approval logic in isolation, but the actual behavior being tested is the wiring between these two modules.\n\nThe full end-to-end sequence — reading the thread, generating a draft, fact-checking, and presenting for approval — requires multiple agentic steps working together on a realistic email. This is a workflow-level test since it involves the LLM, multiple sequential steps, and real email data flowing through the system.\n\nSo I'm settling on: three agentic tests for LLM output quality, factual consistency, and behavior with missing knowledge, one integration test for the approval gate blocking send, and one workflow test for the complete sequence. Now I'm assigning probability distributions across the five levels for each behavior. The first behavior is heavily weighted toward Agentic at 85%, with minimal Unit and System probability. The second behavior also leans Agentic but with more Integration possibility at 10%. The third behavior is more uncertain—only 60% Agentic with a notable 25% Integration chance, reflecting the ambiguity about whether the disclaimer comes from code logic or LLM behavior. The fourth behavior is clearly Integration-focused at 55%, and the fifth is almost entirely Workflow at 85%.\n\nNow I'm reconsidering behavior 3 more closely. I'm leaning toward Agentic for behavior 1 since the disclaimer inclusion depends on the LLM following instructions rather than just code logic, though Integration has some merit. For behavior 2, the factual consistency check likely relies on semantic understanding through an LLM or embeddings, so that's Agentic. Now I'm running through the rejection gate—behaviors 1, 2, and 3 all come down to individual LLM steps rather than multi-step workflows or code-level integration, so they're all Agentic. Behavior 4 should stay at Integration since it's really just verifying the approval state blocks the send action, and Behavior 5 is correctly a Workflow test for the full pipeline.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9697,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9697},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c4c66c1e-67ea-409e-a6c1-4bb837798d5b","uuid":"9f45c424-9122-4ced-ad6a-893e7204a9e1"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Erx17tmh6QMYrhsiZZhswV","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_013iXfVFEuNx53FBLQs3cvXx","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The generated reply references specific points from the incoming email rather than producing a generic response.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"MOCK-MISS: This is squarely about LLM output quality — a mock LLM will always return whatever you hardcode, so it trivially passes and hides the real failure. LLM-DEP: Whether the reply actually references specific thread content (vs. a generic boilerplate) depends entirely on what the real LLM produces; 100 runs may produce varying quality. A mocked LLM cannot reproduce the failure mode. REAL-INFRA: No OS/subprocess dependency specific to this behavior. MULTI-STEP: Only one LLM generation step is under test here. REJECTION-GATE: Considered Workflow — rejected because this behavior isolates a single generation step, not a multi-step pipeline.","test_description":"Submit a real email thread with several specific, named facts (e.g., a scheduled meeting time, a mentioned project name, a quoted figure) to the live LLM-backed draft generator. Assert that the returned draft text contains explicit references to those specific facts rather than a generic opener like 'Thank you for your email.'","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.85,"Workflow":0.07}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The factual consistency check flags claims in the draft that contradict entries in the knowledge base.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The consistency checker must perform semantic reasoning to determine whether a draft claim contradicts a KB entry; this cannot be reduced to keyword matching or deterministic lookup. LLM-DEP: 'Contradicts' is a semantic judgment — distinguishing 'our pricing is $50/month' (contradicts KB entry of $45/month) from 'pricing may vary' (no contradiction) requires real LLM/ML inference. A mock that always returns 'no contradiction' or 'contradiction' would trivially pass or fail. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the checker always hides whether the underlying model correctly identifies contradictions. REJECTION-GATE: Considered Integration — rejected because even if the surrounding wiring is deterministic, the classification of whether a claim contradicts a KB entry is a semantic ML judgment whose failure only surfaces with the real model.","test_description":"Prepare a knowledge base entry with a specific factual claim (e.g., 'feature X is not available in the free tier'). Feed the real consistency checker a draft that asserts the opposite (e.g., 'feature X is available on all plans'). Assert the checker returns a flagged contradiction for that claim. Repeat with a draft that correctly states the KB claim to confirm no false positive.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.74,"Workflow":0.1}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When the knowledge base has no relevant entries, the draft includes a disclaimer rather than fabricating facts.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is LLM hallucination — the LLM silently fabricates plausible-sounding facts when the KB returns no hits, rather than flagging uncertainty. A code-level conditional that appends a fixed disclaimer string would pass at Integration, but that path does not exercise whether the LLM itself respects the 'no information available' signal. LLM-DEP: Whether the generated text includes a genuine disclaimer vs. invented facts depends on real LLM behavior; this varies across runs and model versions. REJECTION-GATE: Considered Integration — rejected because the behavior specifically names fabrication as the failure, which is LLM output behavior, not a code-path branch. If the system relies on a deterministic post-processing step to inject the disclaimer, that sub-behavior is Integration, but the stated failure ('fabricating facts') is only observable with a real LLM.","test_description":"Configure the knowledge base to return zero entries for all queries. Submit an email thread that would require factual claims to answer (e.g., asking about a product's SLA). Invoke the real LLM-backed draft generator and assert: (a) the draft contains a recognizable disclaimer phrase signaling uncertainty or lack of information, and (b) the draft does not assert specific factual claims that are absent from the KB.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.27,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.62,"Workflow":0.06}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The approval workflow blocks sending until the user explicitly approves — no draft is sent automatically.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure is a control-flow boundary between the approval-state module and the send module — e.g., send is invoked before the approval flag is set, or there is a race condition in the state machine. This failure only appears when both modules are wired together. Unit testing the approval state in isolation would not catch a bug where the orchestrator calls send() prematurely. REAL-INFRA: No OS, subprocess, or real network dependency is needed; an in-process fake send stub suffices to observe whether send is invoked without approval. LLM-DEP: No LLM output determines whether send is blocked — this is deterministic control flow. REJECTION-GATE: Considered Unit — rejected because the failure manifests at the module boundary between the approval state tracker and the send action, not inside a single function. Considered Agentic — rejected because the blocking behavior is deterministic; LLM output does not affect whether send is called.","test_description":"Wire the approval workflow component to a stub send function that records whether it was called. Drive the workflow to the 'draft ready' state without providing user approval. Assert the stub send was not called. Then provide explicit approval and assert the stub send is called exactly once.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.1,"Workflow":0.04}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The full sequence — read thread, generate draft, check facts, present for approval — works end-to-end for a real email thread.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"MULTI-STEP: This behavior explicitly describes multiple agentic steps in sequence: (1) read/parse thread, (2) LLM draft generation, (3) LLM/ML-based factual consistency check, (4) approval gating. Each step's output feeds the next; failures may emerge only from the composition (e.g., the consistency checker receives malformed draft output from generation, or the approval gate receives an unexpected structure from the fact-check step). LLM-DEP: At least two steps (generation and consistency check) depend on real LLM outputs. REJECTION-GATE: Considered Agentic — rejected because there are at least two sequential real-LLM steps, and the inter-step data contract (draft format consumed by the fact-checker) is only exercised in the full pipeline. A single Agentic test of generation in isolation would not catch failures at the generation→fact-check handoff.","test_description":"Run the complete pipeline against a realistic email thread fixture with known KB entries (some matching, some contradicting draft claims). Assert that: the draft is non-empty and references thread content; the consistency report identifies the known contradiction; the send action is not triggered before explicit approval is given; after simulated approval, the pipeline reaches the 'ready to send' terminal state. Use real LLM calls for generation and fact-checking steps.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.02,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.08,"Workflow":0.85}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9697,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9697},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c4c66c1e-67ea-409e-a6c1-4bb837798d5b","uuid":"d2be701a-d727-40f2-b1f3-2f998c8dc801"}
